%N A396330 Consider the square spiral with its cells numbered starting at 0. Three players, Red, Green and Blue, take turns and place knights at the smallest unoccupied cell not attacked by an opposing knight, where Red is only opposed by Blue, Green by Red and Blue by Green. Sequence lists squares occupied by a Red knight.
%C A396330 This is a three-player variation of the two-player game on a square spiral (A392177).
%C A396330 Also, a variation of the three-player game on a square spiral (A395645), except that here players can be protected from certain other players' attacks. We use the simplest version: a cyclic protection where Red is protected from Green (only opposed by Blue), Green is protected from Blue (only opposed by Red), and Blue is protected from Red (only opposed by Green). If a player of color i is protected from a player of color j, then i may place pieces in cells under attack by Player j, effectively ignoring the threats from their attacks. Pieces may never be placed in occupied cells and pieces are never removed.
%C A396330 As the number of terms grows, the occupied cells form undulating bands that radiate outward from the center, with the three players' pieces alternating between bands. These regular bands are interspersed with irregular regions where pieces from all three players intermix (see linked illustrations).
